 of Amazons. Hope had heard tales of this unique Amazon tribe which held two ruling Queens, one for war time and one for peace. If her scouts had been correct, Queen Janier and Queen Areto were the last documented rulers of this land, but that had been so many months ago. And since held to her pattern of doing away with messangers, so that she could monopolize on information as power, it was unlikely that those informants of old could be matched by current trackers and scouts. Hope was learning that unless written or verbal word was left with allied tribes, much of Amazon history could conceivable go unnoticed and unremembered. <br>
<br>
The Amazons of the Crimson Stone were known to prize their masks. Hope was not sure if they were merely ceremonial respect to the wildlife surround the tribe, or if possibly there was some lycanthropic power granted by them. She would certainly like to have collected some of the masks for study. But alas, none were available. And her intentions were not set on the masks but the burial markers and runes she had travelled so far to find.<br>
<br>
On this day there were two men in the tribal burial ground area. Hope had heard some tribes allowed for men, though they were never of an leadership position. These men seemed to fit that description. Clearly by their behavior toward her and dress they were servants, caretakers only too pleased to see what they thought was a returning member of the tribe. They were very helpful. Overly so but Hope imagined they had grown worried of the Amazons' absence.<br>
<br>
Hope could have asked them of greater detail of this absence. She could have asked of the masks. She could  have spared their lives, but she had no time for any of those thoughts. All that remained important to her were the stones she had collected. As she walked down the grassy hillside, past the two men of the tribe, caretakers now dead, she made her way to the east, toward the Amazon lands of Orio-Pata.<br>
